\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\sa200\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af3\langfe255\hich\f3\fs22\lang1033\loch\f3\fs22\lang1033{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f3\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0\rtlch\ltrch\hich\f2\loch\f2 [52]\tab We have found that the basis of competition in the glaze market is not merely price but also quality and service levels.  Ferro\'92s entry into the glaze market did not exercise any downward pressure on the price of glaze.  Barriers to entry are relative
ly high and large customers such as tile manufacturers exercised considerable countervailing power and were able to extract volume discounts in the form of rebates. Large customers such as CIL had the resources to facilitate new entry in the glaze market i
n the event of price increases or quality concerns.   Smaller consumers of glaze however did not enjoy such countervailing power. We conclude that the horizontal effects of the transaction will not lead to the removal of an effective competitor.  Spectrum 
was already the leading producer of glaze and seemingly could engage in unilateral conduct pre-merger.  Despite the high barriers to entry in the glaze market the vertical integration of Ferro and Spectrum is unlikely to lead to higher prices for large cus
tomers with countervailing power.  These large customers are able to negotiate large volume discounts in the form of rebates and also have the resources to establish relationships with other glaze producers or to facilitate entry of new glaze producers in 
the glaze market. However the vertical integration of Ferro and Spectrum could possibly lead to higher prices for smaller customers who do not enjoy countervailing power, as suggested by Mr Kromm.  Clause 10.4 of the sale of shares agreement and Ferro\'92s co
rrespondence suggest that Ferro did intend to supply frit at a premium to Spectrum.  }
